Is anyone working on the future of coding internal apps and tools? In every company I've worked for we've had a fairly large internal web app that didn't get as much love

As I understand it, Heroku hosts your app, but doesn't give you access to the OS. So it's like AWS with restrictions.

I wonder if we're talking about the same thing?

For clarification, I'm looking to the UI side of the future of internal apps. There might be some way to go from data to a UI similarly to how they use procedural generation in games (I know it's a stretch)
If you haven't seen it, <https://tryretool.com/>

attachments.title: Retool – build internal tools fast
attachments.text: Build custom internal tools in minutes. Build an interface via our drag-and-drop UI, hook it up to your data, and you're done.

text: They even say "internal tools" in the name :heart_eyes:
Exactly!
Now we just gotta figure out how to go directly from data to a UI
that sounds rather like Filemaker Pro
heroku is sort of an improved API to a linux hosting environment
it's containers, a build-system to make containers out of git repos, traffic delivery, log collection and various and sundry other niceties like CI, databases, and team management

I see. I'm a frontend dev so I some have misconceptions about backend. I think it's a good sign if as you're coding you end up with parts resembling actual products. You might be walking in the footsteps of the Heroku guys.
Good abstractions tend to re-appear if you're not explicitly trying to re-invent them

Tyretool is basically a web version of Filemaker Pro without any of the graphical customization possibilities at $10/user/month, so slightly cheaper than filemaker pro pricing for small user bases, but a great deal more expensive for large numbers of users. Filemaker Pro may still have a poor scripting language, but it is extremely powerful, and i have used Filemaker Pro many times for small databases because it is so easy to work with, and so well documented at this point, being 20+ years old. Filemaker Pro is one of those products like Delphi that gets zero love because it is so simple.

Yes. It will have a “personal memex” / community knowledge base orientation, so I think ingesting and publishing data will come first. Interop would be an extension of that.
One of my guiding ideas is that different relationships and communities need different things out of their communication/collaboration channels, but that that’s not a reason to have totally different and siloed tools. [May 27th, 2020 12:38 PM] zspotting: Hey everyone, long time lurker here! I'm a software engineer in San Francisco. Over the last couple years, I've been playing with a handful of flow-based programming tools and prototyping my own. My main interest is in tools that make programming more accessible to everyone, especially those without technical backgrounds. I believe that the flow paradigm is intuitive and flexible enough to become a mainstream interface that everyone can use to manage their data, devices, etc.

I started working as a fullstack eng at <http://Parabola.io|Parabola.io> just a couple months ago. It's a web-based flow tool for connecting and processing data from a wide range of other cloud platforms. Think flow programming meets IFTTT meets Excel. It's been an interesting shift in mindset, going from daydreaming about a flowy future to building a product that needs to solve practical needs for users! :slightly_smiling_face: It's a fun challenge, and I hope to share a few insights in the future!

Hopefully you'll see me jump into some conversations around Slack and Twitter. And if you're playing with Parabola, I'd love to know what you think. Please reach out if you need a hand with anything (tech issues, feature requests, pricing, etc)
attachments.text:
Hey everyone, long time lurker here! I'm a software engineer in San Francisco. Over the last couple years, I've been playing with a handful of flow-based programming tools and prototyping my own. My main interest is in tools that make programming more accessible to everyone, especially those without technical backgrounds. I believe that the flow paradigm is intuitive and flexible enough to become a mainstream interface that everyone can use to manage their data, devices, etc.

I started working as a fullstack eng at <http://Parabola.io|Parabola.io> just a couple months ago. It's a web-based flow tool for connecting and processing data from a wide range of other cloud platforms. Think flow programming meets IFTTT meets Excel. It's been an interesting shift in mindset, going from daydreaming about a flowy future to building a product that needs to solve practical needs for users! :slightly_smiling_face: It's a fun challenge, and I hope to share a few insights in the future!

Hopefully you'll see me jump into some conversations around Slack and Twitter. And if you're playing with Parabola, I'd love to know what you think. Please reach out if you need a hand with anything (tech issues, feature requests, pricing, etc)
